## âœ… 1. Auto-Mount USB on Boot

### ğŸ§ª First, find the USB device:

```bash
lsblk
```

Letâ€™s say the USB is `/dev/sda1`.

### ğŸ†” Get its UUID:

```bash
sudo blkid /dev/sda1
```

Youâ€™ll get something like:

```bash
UUID="AB12-34CD" TYPE="vfat"
```

### ğŸ“ Edit `/etc/fstab`:

```bash
sudo nano /etc/fstab
```

Add this line at the bottom:

```fstab
UUID=AB12-34CD  /media/pi/paperless-usb  vfat  defaults,nofail,uid=1000,gid=1000  0  0
```

> ğŸ” Replace with your actual UUID and filesystem type (`vfat`, `ext4`, etc.)

Then test it:

```bash
sudo mount -a
```

Check:

```bash
ls /media/pi/paperless-usb
```

Your USB should now auto-mount on every boot.

